│ An analysis of the issue and the proposed fix is as follows: │
│                                                              │
│ ### 1. Understanding the Issue                               │
│                                                              │
│ The `vector-combine` pass is crashing with a `SIGABRT`       │
│ signal due to a failed assertion: `isa<To>(Val) &&           │
│ "cast<Ty>() argument of incompatible type!"`. This occurs    │
│ within the `foldShuffleToIdentity` function when trying to   │
│ cast a `Type*` to a `FixedVectorType`. The backtrace         │
│ indicates that this happens while processing a               │
│ `shufflevector` instruction. The core of the problem is that │
│ an instruction, which is expected to have a vector type, has │
│ a non-vector type, leading to the illegal cast.              │
│                                                              │
│ ### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log                                 │
│                                                              │
│ The crash occurs in `foldShuffleToIdentity` when processing  │
│ the second `shufflevector` instruction (`%shufflevector1`)   │
│ in the provided reproducer. This function attempts to        │
│ optimize a chain of `shufflevector` instructions. The        │
│ reproducer shows the following pattern:                      │
│                                                              │
│ ```llvm                                                      │
│ %call = call <4 x i64> @llvm.fshl.v4i64(...) [               │
│ "jl_roots"(...) ]                                            │
│ %shufflevector = shufflevector <4 x i64> %call, ...          │
│ %shufflevector1 = shufflevector <16 x i64> %shufflevector,   │
│ ...                                                          │
│ ```                                                          │
│                                                              │
│ The crash happens when `foldShuffleToIdentity` inspects      │
│ `%shufflevector`, which is an operand of `%shufflevector1`.  │
│ The function expects the operand of a `shufflevector` to     │
│ have a vector type. The assertion failure implies that at    │
│ some point, the type of an instruction that should be a      │
│ vector has been corrupted.                                   │
│                                                              │
│ The presence of an operand bundle on the `@llvm.fshl.v4i64`  │
│ call is a critical detail. Operand bundles are a less common │
│ feature and can expose bugs in optimization passes that do   │
│ not handle them correctly.                                   │
│                                                              │
│ ### 3. Root Cause Analysis                                   │
│                                                              │
│ The root cause of this crash is not in `vector-combine`      │
│ itself but in an earlier simplification pass, specifically   │
│ `InstSimplify`. The `InstSimplify` pass contains logic to    │
│ optimize patterns like `shufflevector(call(...))` into       │
│ `call(shufflevector(...))`. This transformation is generally │
│ valid, but the implementation has a flaw: it does not        │
│ correctly handle `call` instructions that have operand       │
│ bundles.                                                     │
│                                                              │
│ When `InstSimplify` encounters the first `shufflevector`     │
│ (`%shufflevector`), it tries to sink the shuffle into the    │
│ `call` instruction. It creates a new `call` instruction but  │
│ fails to propagate the operand bundles from the original     │
│ `call`. This results in a malformed `call` instruction being │
│ created. The newly created instruction is then used to       │
│ replace the original `shufflevector`.                        │
│                                                              │
│ The malformed `call` instruction, now replacing              │
│ `%shufflevector`, does not have a proper vector type. When   │
│ the `vector-combine` pass later runs and analyzes            │
│ `%shufflevector1`, it sees this malformed instruction as an  │
│ operand. The `foldShuffleToIdentity` function, assuming it   │
│ is dealing with valid IR, attempts to get the vector type of │
│ this operand, which fails because the type is not a          │
│ `FixedVectorType`, leading to the `cast` assertion failure.  │
│                                                              │
│ The fix is to make the `InstSimplify` transformation aware   │
│ of operand bundles and prevent it from firing when they are  │
│ present on the `call` instruction.                           │
│                                                              │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                │
│                                                              │
│ The issue can be resolved by adding a check in               │
│ `InstSimplify.cpp` to ensure that the `call` instruction     │
│ does not have operand bundles before attempting the          │
│ `shuffle(call) -> call(shuffle)` transformation.             │
│                                                              │
│ - **File**: `llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/InstSimplify.cpp`     │
│ - **Edit Point**: Add a check for operand bundles within the │
│ `simplifyShuffleVectorInst` function.                        │
│                                                              │
│ ```cpp                                                       │
│ // llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/InstSimplify.cpp                │
│                                                              │
│ // shuffle(call) -> call(shuffle)                            │
│ if (auto *CI = dyn_cast<CallInst>(V1)) {                     │
│   // Don't change the argument to a call if it is a varargs  │
│ call.                                                        │
│   if (CI->getFunctionType()->isVarArg())                     │
│     return SD;                                               │
│                                                              │
│   // Don't change the argument to a call if it has operand   │
│ bundles.                                                     │
│   if (CI->hasOperandBundles())                               │
│     return SD;                                               │
│                                                              │
│   // The shuffle is only moving around arguments of the      │
│ call.                                                        │
│   // See if we can create a new call with the shuffled       │
│ arguments.                                                   │
│   if (isShuffleOfOperandsOf(SI, CI)) {                       │
│ ```                                                          │
│                                                              │
│ ### 5. Conclusion                                            │
│                                                              │
│ The crash in `vector-combine` is a symptom of incorrect IR   │
│ being generated by `InstSimplify`. The proposed edit         │
│ addresses the root cause by preventing `InstSimplify` from   │
│ incorrectly transforming `call` instructions with operand    │
│ bundles. This ensures that the IR remains valid, thus        │
│ preventing the subsequent crash in the `vector-combine`      │
│ pass. This fix improves the robustness of the optimizer when │
│ dealing with less common LLVM IR features like operand       │
│ bundles.                                                     │
